content:
What Makes Bots Tick?

Bots have many moving parts. But let’s start with a few fundamental components in Einstein Bots.

Dialogs are conversation snippets that control what your bot can do. You can associate every dialog with a dialog intent, which can be trained to understand variations in customer input. During a conversation with a customer, your bot moves between several different dialogs. Each dialog handles a portion of the conversation.

Entity represents a type of data that you want to collect from a customer. We provide system entities and you can create custom ones as needed.

Intents are the customer's reasons for interacting with your bot. Associate intents with your dialogs. Then train the bot to create an intent model that your bot can use to understand intents.

Named Entity Recognition (NER) identifies data inside of bot conversations and maintains the format of that data.

Natural Language Processing (NLP) is how your bot processes the free text that your customers enter into your bot. NLP combines ideas and methods from computer science, linguistics, and AI to train your bot to identify the literal, grammatical, and contextual meanings of your customers’ inputs.

Utterances are common conversational phrases that represent the ways your customers describe an intent. Utterances are the building blocks of intent models.

A variable is a container that stores a specific piece of data collected from the customer or output from Salesforce. Variables can be used within dialog actions as both inputs and outputs and can be inserted as part of the text in messages.

Intent: Transfer to agent

Utterances:

* I’d like to speak to an agent.
* Can I talk to a person?
* Agent

Variable examples:

* Airport Code
	+ Departure Airport Code
	+ Arrival Airport Code
title: Understanding Einstein Bots in Service Cloud
